{"cursor":"7730","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox Weapon |name= Fusil M-1908 \"MondragÃ³n\" |image= |caption= MondragÃ³n\nrifle with a rifle sling |origin= [http://world.guns.ru/rifle/autoloading-rifles/switch/mondragon-\ne.html Modern Firearms - Mondragon ] |type= Semi-\nautomatic rifle Automatic rifle Light machine gun \n|is_ranged=yes  |service= 1887â1918 (Mexico and\nGermany)) |used_by = See ''Users'' |wars= Mexican Revolution World War I  |designer= General Manuel MondragÃ³n |design_date= 1887\n|manufacturer=Schweizerische Industrie Gesellschaft |production_date= 1887\n|number= 4,000 |variants= Automatic rifle Light machine gun.  |weight= empty |length= |barrel_length= |crew=  |caliber= 7mm Mauser 7.65 Argentine 7.5 Swiss 30-30\n|cartridge= 7Ã57mm Mauser |action= gas-operated, rotating bolt |rate= 750â1400\nrounds/min depending on variant |velocity= 710 m/s (2300 ft/s) |range= 200 m to\n550 m sight marks |max_range= |feed= 8 round box, 10 round box, 20\nround box, 30 round drum, 100 round drum |sights= Iron sights }} The\n'MondragÃ³n' was a Mexican battle rifle and the world's first automatic\nrifle. [http://www.cruffler.com/historic-february01.html\nHistoric Firearm of the Month, February 2001 ]\nIt was designed by Mexican general Manuel MondragÃ³n and was the first fully\nautomatic firearm able to be operated by a single rifleman.\n\nMondragÃ³n began his work in 1882 and patented the weapon in 1887. It was gas-\noperated with a cylinder and piston arrangement, now very familiar but unusual\nat the time, and rotating bolt, locked by lugs in helical grooves in the\nreceiver; it was also possible to operate it as a simple straight-pull bolt\naction. The caliber was 7mm (.284 in) Mauser and the rifle was available with\neither an 8-round or 20-round box magazine, or a 100-round drum magazine (for\nvariants produced after 1910).\n","linknr":216,"url":"Mondragón_rifle","recorded":1375090528,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Mondrag%C3%